namespace MiniSpinGeometry

/-! ## L7: Exterior Algebra Connection

The exterior algebra Lambda(V) and the Clifford algebra Cl(V, Q)
are isomorphic as filtered vector spaces via the quantization map:

  q: Lambda^k(V) -> Cl(V),  v_1 wedge ... wedge v_k
     |-> (1/k!) sum_{sigma in S_k} sgn(sigma) v_{sigma(1)} ... v_{sigma(k)}

The inverse is the symbol map:
  sigma: Cl(V) -> Lambda(V),  e_{i_1}...e_{i_k} |-> e_{i_1} wedge ... wedge e_{i_k}

The associated graded algebra of Cl(V) is Lambda(V).
-/

def quantizationSymbolMap : String :=
  "q: Lambda(V) <-> Cl(V) :sigma (vector space isomorphism)"

/-! ## L7: Connection to Lie Groups and Lie Algebras

The spin group Spin(n) sits inside the even Clifford algebra Cl^0(n).
Its Lie algebra spin(n) = span{e_i e_j : i < j} in Cl^0(n).

The Lie bracket: [x, y] = xy - yx (commutator in the Clifford algebra).

Isomorphism of Lie algebras:
  spin(3) = su(2) = so(3)
  spin(4) = su(2) + su(2) = so(4)
  spin(5) = sp(2)
  spin(6) = su(4)
-/

def spinLieAlgebra (n : Nat) : String :=
  match n with
  | 3 => "spin(3) = su(2)"
  | 4 => "spin(4) = su(2) + su(2)"
  | 5 => "spin(5) = sp(2)"
  | 6 => "spin(6) = su(4)"
  | _ => s!"spin({n})"

/-! ## L7: Group Presentations from pi_1

The fundamental group of a CW complex can be presented via
generators (1-cells) and relations (2-cells).

For a spin manifold, pi_1 gives information about spin structures:
  Hom(pi_1(M), Z/2) = H^1(M, Z/2) classifies spin structures.

Examples of surface group presentations:
  pi_1(Sigma_g) = <a_1,b_1,...,a_g,b_g | prod [a_i,b_i] = 1>
-/

def surfaceGroupPresentation (g : Nat) : String :=
  s!"pi_1(Sigma_{g}) = <a_1,b_1,...,a_{g},b_{g} | prod [a_i,b_i] = 1>"

#eval surfaceGroupPresentation 1
#eval surfaceGroupPresentation 2

/-! ## L7: Spin Representation and Young Tableaux

The spin representations of Spin(n) can be constructed via
Clifford modules. For low dimensions, they relate to fundamental
representations of classical Lie groups:

Spin(2k): two half-spin irreps S^+, S^- (dim 2^{k-1})
Spin(2k+1): one spin irrep S (dim 2^k)

These correspond to the spin nodes in the Dynkin diagram.
-/

/-! ## L8: The Brauer-Wall Group BW(R)

The Brauer-Wall group BW(R) = Z/8 classifies graded central
simple R-algebras up to graded Morita equivalence.

The generator is [Cl(1,0)] (the graded Clifford algebra of R^1
with negative definite quadratic form).

BW(R) encodes the Bott periodic classification of Clifford
algebras and real K-theory.

BW(R) = {[Cl(p,q)] : p,q in N} / graded Morita equivalence
-/

def brauerWallGroupDesc : String :=
  "BW(R) = Z/8, generated by [Cl(1,0)], encodes Bott periodicity"

/-! ## L8: Real K-Theory Connection

KO^{-n}(pt) classifies stable homotopy classes of maps S^n -> BO.
The Bott periodicity KO^{-n-8}(pt) = KO^{-n}(pt) is proven via
Clifford algebras:

  KO^{-n}(pt) = pi_n(BO)
  KO^0(pt) = Z
  KO^{-1}(pt) = Z/2
  KO^{-2}(pt) = Z/2
  KO^{-3}(pt) = 0
  KO^{-4}(pt) = Z
  KO^{-5}(pt) = 0
  KO^{-6}(pt) = 0
  KO^{-7}(pt) = 0

These groups are the alpha-invariant targets for spin cobordism.
-/

def realKTheoryPoints : List String := [
  "KO^0(pt)=Z", "KO^{-1}(pt)=Z/2", "KO^{-2}(pt)=Z/2",
  "KO^{-3}(pt)=0", "KO^{-4}(pt)=Z", "KO^{-5}(pt)=0",
  "KO^{-6}(pt)=0", "KO^{-7}(pt)=0"
]

#eval "KO^{-n}(pt): " ++ toString realKTheoryPoints

